  "reveal": {
    "ledger_voiced": "The raps came from my knee against the table's leaf, twice and thrice as needed. The spirit writing was managed by exchanging the slates in the dark—chalk-crumb on my cuff bore witness to the work. The touch was a kid glove stuffed with wool, kept on the ice beforehand, pressed to skin when the moment called. The lamp's guttering I had arranged by trimming the wick short at six o'clock; it wanted ten minutes to fail entirely. The cold draught issued from the window cord, loosed an inch before the lamps went out. My own voice, thrown low, supplied the whispered words—grief hears what it is owed, and hears it gladly. The spirit trumpet moved by black silk thread and the reach of a practised arm.\n\nXerxes Hartfield murdered Cousin R. His hands were not in the circle that night; they were occupied elsewhere, doing work no apparatus of mine could claim. He had arranged the dark as a veil, but not for my effects. Cousin R was found past any sitting's reach, past any medium's power to summon back.\n\nThe dead say only what the living require them to say, and on this occasion, Xerxes required them to say nothing at all.",
